  "opinion": "As a barista in New York with a vocational diploma and a creative mindset, I’ve seen how stereotype threat in STEM can quietly undermine potential. Stereotype threat isn’t just a theory—it’s the weight of being told you don’t belong in a field where your identity feels mismatched. For me, it’s the moment a student in my coffee shop mentions they’re struggling with math because they’re ‘not good at it’—a phrase that echoes the same anxiety I’ve heard from others who feel their gender, race, or background makes them outliers in science classrooms. I’ve noticed how even small things, like the way teachers phrase questions or the lack of role models who look like me, can make someone hesitate to try. But here’s what I believe: we must address it, not with grand gestures but through subtle, consistent actions. For example, when I mentor young people who want to pursue STEM, I avoid saying things like ‘you’ll never be good at this’ and instead focus on their curiosity and problem-solving skills. It’s about creating spaces where everyone feels safe to explore without the fear of being judged for who they are. My own journey—growing up in a family where one parent has a master’s and the other doesn’t—taught me that confidence comes from seeing yourself reflected in the world around you. So, addressing stereotype threat means making sure classrooms and labs aren’t just full of people who fit a certain mold but are built to welcome all kinds of minds. It’s not about fixing the problem but helping people realize their potential isn’t limited by the stereotypes they’ve internalized.",
